Closing the gap in world health and economics - a data analysis project to convey the fact-based worldview¶

  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

In this data analysis project, I intend to convey fact-based view about the world health and economics. Specifically, I have used data from Gapminder.org to attempt to answer the following two questions:

How does the income inequality across countries affect people's life expectancy and child mortality rate in their communities?

Has the income inequality across countries worsened or gotten better in the last 60 years? What impact did this change have on life expectancy and child mortality rate?

To aid in my analysis, I downloaded the following four datasets in .csv format from Gapminder.org:

  1. GDP per capita - This dataset contains income per person (GDP per person adjusted for inflation and converted to international dollars using purchasing power parity), GDP total and GDP per capita growth % listed by country name for every year since 1800.

  2. Child mortality - This dataset contains child mortality rate (death of children under five year of age per 1000 live birth) listed by country name for every year since 1800.

  3. Life expectancy - This dataset contains life expectancy rate (the average number of years a newborn child would live if the current mortality patterns were to remain the same) listed by country name for every year since 1800.

  4. Population - This dataset contains total population listed by country name for every year since 1800.

To answer the questions, I will be analyzing and comparing the relationship between income, life expectancy and child mortality for two different years: 1960 and 2020.

# funtion to load the data into dataframe
def load_data(filename):
    """
    This function reads a .csv file and loads into a dataframe
    argument: .csv file name
    returns: dataframe
    """
    df = pd.read_csv(filename)
    return df

Cleaning the data¶

Here, I am renaming the column headers and dropping the columns that I don't require.

In [4]:
# funtion to standarize the column headings
def standardize_columns(df):
    """
    This function 
        1. drops unwanted columns: 'geo', 'GDP total', 'GDP per capita growth (%)' 
        (Note: if the column name is not present in the dataframe, it will ignore)
        2. replaces any space in the column name with underscore
        3. makes column name to all lower cases
        4. renames column name "name" to "country" and "time" to "year"
    argument: dataframe
    returns: updated dataframe
    """
    df.drop(['geo', 'GDP total', 'GDP per capita growth (%)'], axis = 1, inplace = True, errors = 'ignore')
    df.rename(columns = lambda x: x.strip().lower().replace(" ", "_"), inplace = True)
    df.rename(columns = {"name": "country", "time": "year"}, inplace = True)
    return df
In [5]:

df_life_expectancy = standardize_columns(df_life_expectancy)
df_population = standardize_columns(df_population)

Selecting rows¶

Here, I am selecting the rows where the year = '1960' or '2020'

In [6]:
# function to select specific rows from a dataframe
def select_rows(df):
    """
    This function selects only the rows where 'year' is equal to 1960 or 2020
    argument: dataframe
    returns: dataframe with only specific rows
    """
    df = df.loc[df['year'].isin([1960, 2020])]
    return(df)
In [7]:

df_population = select_rows(df_population)

There is no null value in the merged dataframe and it has only the columns I intend to use for analysis. The income_per_person is the annual income. Though it can be used for analysis, a better value will be dollars_per_day. Luckily, income_per_person is an integer and I can divide it by 365 to get the dollars_per_day.

I also need a categorical variable for income. I will be creating one in the next section.

Creating new columns¶

Here, I am creating two new variables/columns:

  • dollars_per_day --> a continuous variable created by dividing income_per_person by 365.
  • income_levels --> a categorical variable created by grouping dollars_per_day into 4 different buckets, namely less than 8 dollars per day, between 8 and 16 dollars per day, between 16 and 32 dollars per day and more than 32 dollars per day. I don't want to use the terms "poor" or "rich" to categorize countries/people, because those terms are subjective and majority of the people live somewhere in the middle. I have used the following categories to group the countries by their income level:
    • 1-Meagre - average daily income of less than 8 dollars
    • 2-Low - average daily income between 8 and 16 dollars
    • 3-Medium - average daily income between 16 and 32 dollars
    • 4-High - average daily income of more than 32 dollars
In [12]:
# create a new column 'dollars_per_day'

# define the bin edges in order to categorise based on dollars_per_day
income_level_bin_edges = [1.13, 8.00, 16.00, 32.00, 303.08]

# define the name for each bin

# create a new column 'income_levels' based on dollars_per_day
df['income_levels'] = pd.cut(df['dollars_per_day'], income_level_bin_edges, labels = income_level_bins)

How did the dollars per day or income levels impact life expectancy and child mortality? Let's find out next.

From the above graph, it is very apparent that the life expectancy and the child mortality were very much impacted by the countries' income levels. Countries with meagre income level were characterized by high child mortality and low life expectancy, while the countries with high income level had just the opposite.

A reminder about income levels:

  • 1-Meagre --> countries with daily average income of 8.00 dollars or less
  • 2-Low --> countries with daily average income between 8.00 and 16.00 dollars
  • 3-Medium --> countries with daily average income between 16.00 and 32.00 dollars
  • 4-High --> countries with daily average income of 32.00 dollars or more

Let's plot some graphs by income levels and see how the variation in life expectancy and child mortality are crystal clear among the various income levels.

In 1960, nearly 50% (87 out of 186) of the countries were in the meagre income level with their people earning daily average income of 8 dollars or less. In 2020, that number dropped to 32 countries or 17%. On the contrary, in 1960, only 23 countries (or 12%) were in the high income level. In 2020, that number increased to 94 countries (or 50%).

From the numbers, it is clear that many countries moved up the income levels between 1960 and 2020, closing the gap in income inequalities. Let's confirm this by considering how the population varied by income levels between 1960 and 2020. In order to do the comparison, let's first calculate total population and population percentage by income levels for each year: 1960 and 2020.

In [28]:
# sum the population by year and then by income_levels
population_total = df.groupby(['year', 'income_levels']).sum()['population']

# find the proportion of population by income_levels for each year (1960 and 2020)
population_percent = population_total.groupby(level=0).apply(lambda x: 100 * x / float(x.sum()))

# convert the total/percent series into dataframe and reset the index for using to plot graphs
population_total = population_total.to_frame().reset_index()
population_percent = population_percent.to_frame().reset_index()
print(population_total)
print(population_percent)

    ax = axes[1,0],
    data = df,
    x = "income_levels", 
    y = "life_expectancy",
    hue = "year"
)

# set the labels
axes[1,0].set_xlabel("Income levels")
axes[1,0].set_ylabel("Life expectancy");

# plot the stripplot for child mortality
sns.stripplot(
    ax = axes[0,1],
    data = df,
    x = "income_levels", 
    y = "child_mortality",
    hue = "year"
)

# set the title and labels
axes[0,1].set_title("Variation in child mortality by income levels in 1960 and 2020")
axes[0,1].set_ylabel("Child mortality")

# plot the barplot for child mortality
sns.boxplot(
    ax = axes[1,1],
    data = df,
    x = "income_levels", 
    y = "child_mortality",
    hue = "year"
)

# set the labels
axes[1,1].set_xlabel("Income levels")
axes[1,1].set_ylabel("Child mortality");

Life expectancy - the variation in life expectancy is getting shorter among countries in various income levels. In 1960, the difference in median life expectancy between meagre and high income level countries was almost 25 years. In 2020, that gap has shrunk to almost 10 years.

Child mortality - between 1960 and 2020, the child mortality rate reduced considerably across all income levels. The rate of reduction is higher in the lower income level countries, bringing them closer to the child mortality rate in the higher income level countries.

Conclusions¶

In 1960, the variations in life expectancy and child mortality among countries in various income levels were very prominent. Countries with higher income level were characterized by higher life expectancy and lower child mortality. As we move down the income levels, life expectancy decreased and child mortality increased.

Between 1960 and 2020, the income level of many countries increased. In 60 years, the world moved from a state where "50% of the world population living with a meagre average daily income of 8 dollars or less" to a state where "50% of the world population living with an high average daily income of 32 dollars or more". In other words, income inequality across countries is reducing as more and more countries are moving up the income level in the last 60 years.

The reduction in the income inequality among countries is having a positive effect on life expectancy and child mortality. As the income level of the countries increases, the variations in life expectancy and child mortality among countries in various income levels are reducing at a faster rate. Even though there are still some variations among countries, those variations are not as prominent as they were in 1960. If this trend continues, closing the gap in income, life expectancy, child mortality or any other indicators among countries is not far away.

Limitation: The data provided for income, life expectancy and child mortality are the averages for each country. Within each country, the rates vary widely. The relationship discussed here between income and life expectancy and child mortality holds good only for the averages at the country level. It must be noted that states/provinces from the same country can be quite different and that states/provinces with the same income can have different life expectancy or child mortality rate.
